    "# Next we initialise values needed for our future computations. These have been \n",
    "# provided for us and have been described as reproduction and predation rates.\n",
    "c = 0.000005\n",
    "d = 0.3\n",
    "f = 0.5\n",
    "g = 0.00001"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "680bdcc2-7f6d-428d-9423-5710e5b4f067",
   "metadata": {

   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# First we are defining how many time steps or iterations we will be observing\n",
    "time_steps = 50\n",
    "\n",
    "# Here we are creating lists to store our animal populations over time\n",
    "fox_population_growth = []\n",
    "rabbit_population_growth = []"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "93388dc8-cce0-4498-a8d4-96e8dd5462c5",
   "metadata": {
    "jp-MarkdownHeadingCollapsed": true

   "source": [
    "### Task 4"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 168,
   "id": "78eb7ccf-faee-4ba8-b503-499922f4b423",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Reinitializing parameters we have already set above just incase you run this cell multiple times, the default\n",
    "# values are always the same. (The reason they were assigned above was for assesstment sake)\n",
    "fox_population = 35000\n",
    "rabbit_population = 70000\n",
    "\n",
    "fox_population_growth = []\n",
    "rabbit_population_growth = []\n",
    "\n",
    "# Iterating over all time\n",
    "for step in range(time_steps):\n",
    "    # Generating new population values using a pre given sum and the supplied variables from tasks 1 and 2\n",
    "    new_fox_population = (((c*rabbit_population)-d)*fox_population)+fox_population \n",
    "    new_rabbit_population = ((f-(g*fox_population))*rabbit_population)+rabbit_population\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Using this conditional to control for a negative population, charting a negative population does not\n",
    "    # make much sense, as well as negative numbers will have undesired outcomes on our equations.\n",
    "    if new_rabbit_population < 0:\n",
    "        new_rabbit_population = 0\n",
    "    elif new_fox_population < 0:\n",
    "        new_fox_population = 0\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Appending new population numbers to our above made lists\n",
    "    fox_population_growth.append(new_fox_population)\n",
    "    rabbit_population_growth.append(new_rabbit_population)\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Reassigning our rabbit and fox population variables with the newly calculated rabbit and fox populations\n",
    "    fox_population = new_fox_population\n",
    "    rabbit_population = new_rabbit_population"
   ]
  },
  {

    "So from our above chart, there are a few things that we can infer about the relationship between the populations of <br>\n",
    "the two animals in our experiment:\n",
    "1. It seems that the fox population tends to lag the rabbit population. <br>\n",
    "This makes sense as with lower fox numbers the rabbits are able to reproduce<br>\n",
    "much quicker then when there is a larger number of foxes hunting them.\n",
    "2. As this was an isolated test with no outside elements effecting the results, <br>\n",
    "our data potentially suggests to no control in the form of conservation, may lead <br>\n",
    "to a total population wipe out of both animal species."

    "#### Range Function"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 192,
   "id": "93d0215c-1e0d-4f15-acd7-5f3f0a571a72",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Function to calculate the range of our series\n",
    "def calc_range(*series):\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    Calculates the range of a pandas series\n",
    "    param: Series - series, a pandas dataseries\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    # For each series, get the max and minus the min of the to find the range\n",
    "    for set in series:\n",
    "        range = max(set) - min(set)\n",
    "        print(f\"- Range: {round(range, 4)}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e5e20a4b-4ba6-4f12-b4bc-5c4f1472b670",
   "metadata": {
    "jp-MarkdownHeadingCollapsed": true
   },
   "source": [
    "#### Mean Function"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 195,
   "id": "a604a316-bf51-437c-a39d-8c39c4029c8b",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Function to calculate the average\n",
    "def calc_mean(*series):\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    Calculates the mean of a pandas series\n",
    "    param: Series - series, a pandas dataseries\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    # initialize variables sum and length for calculation\n",
    "    sum, length = 0, 0\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Iterates through all series passed into the function\n",
    "    for set in series:\n",
    "        # Iterates through all values in a given series and adds them together\n",
    "        # into the sum variables, and adds a +1 to the length variable to calc\n",
    "        # how many values appear in the series. We then divide the sum of values\n",
    "        # by the length of the series we round the avg and return that number.\n",
    "        for entry in set:\n",
    "            sum += entry\n",
    "            length+= 1\n",
    "        return round(sum/length, 4)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "2027a37b-4186-46cb-9b50-c63c9a4ca275",
   "metadata": {
    "jp-MarkdownHeadingCollapsed": true
   },
   "source": [
    "#### Median Function"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 198,
   "id": "45f067dd-8ad5-4c76-b686-1bf5316f727e",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Function to calculate the median\n",
    "def calc_median(*series):\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    Calculates the median of a pandas series\n",
    "    param: Series - series, a pandas dataseries\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Iterate through all series\n",
    "    for set in series:\n",
    "        # Using the .sort_values function from pandas to sort our series in\n",
    "        # ascending order.\n",
    "        set.sort_values()\n",
    "\n",
    "        # Using the .size function from pandas to find the mid point of our\n",
    "        # series by dividng the total entries by two and rounding up.\n",
    "        mid_point = round(set.size / 2)\n",
    "        print(f\"- Median: {round(set[mid_point], 4)}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "b4dae342-5f96-41d8-912b-224f29b46c7b",
   "metadata": {
    "jp-MarkdownHeadingCollapsed": true
   },
   "source": [
    "#### Standard Deviation Function"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 201,
   "id": "fb277475-2913-4fc7-bc11-ec6dfd87c006",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Function to calculate the standard deviation\n",
    "import math # needed for square rooting\n",
    "\n",
    "def calc_std(*series):\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    Calculates the standard deviation of a pandas series\n",
    "    param: Series - series, a pandas dataseries\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    # Iterate through each series \n",
    "    for set in series:\n",
    "        # Get the mean for the series\n",
    "        mean = calc_mean(set)\n",
    "\n",
    "        # Subtract the mean from every entry in the series and square the result\n",
    "        deviations = [(entry - mean)**2 for entry in set]\n",
    "\n",
    "        # Get the mean of the above deviations\n",
    "        variance = calc_mean(deviations)\n",
    "\n",
    "        # Take the square root of the above variance to get the standard deviation\n",
    "        std = math.sqrt(variance)\n",
    "\n",
    "        # return the result\n",
    "        return round(std,4)\n",
    "\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a15159ba-f584-421d-ae88-e046171abe0f",
   "metadata": {
    "jp-MarkdownHeadingCollapsed": true
   },
   "source": [
    "#### Total Statistics Function"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 204,
   "id": "333aec37-8446-4b08-b5f8-4d3a95587f61",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def calculate_stats(*series):\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    Calls a series of statistical functions to find the range, mean, median and\n",
    "    standard deviation for any number of given pandas series\n",
    "    param: series, a pandas dataseries\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Iterates through all series\n",
    "    for set in series:\n",
    "        # Prints the series name, and calls all statistical functions for the series.\n",
    "        print(f\"{set.name} Stats:\")\n",
    "        calc_range(set)\n",
    "        print(f\"- Mean: {calc_mean(set)}\")\n",
    "        calc_median(set)\n",
    "        print(f\"- Standard Deviation: {calc_std(set)}\")\n",
    "        print()\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 206,
   "id": "c0d852c2-30e0-43a4-9b91-485f0540f289",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {

    "### Task 3. Time Series Analysis"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 211,
   "id": "08914c74-74d5-463c-a2aa-d8e7ec0d4f21",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Create a function that will plot out all the values in our dataframe onto individual charts\n",
    "def createAChart(x, y, title):\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    Creates a chart of all series passed to it. \n",
    "    \n",
    "    Takes an input, x which is a pandas series for the x-axis and another input, y which is a list\n",
    "    of tuples for the y-axis. It then plots each y-axis values one at a time until there are no \n",
    "    more left, at which point it applies all the style changes, appends a legend and presents the\n",
    "    chart.\n",
    "    params: \n",
    "    - Pandas series: x - the x coordinates for a plot\n",
    "    - List: y - a tuple of all the why values with the desired colour and label for the series\n",
    "    - String : title - the title for the created chart.\n",
    "    Returns: None\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Create the figure\n",
    "    fig, ax=plt.subplots(figsize=(15,6))\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Plot results\n",
    "    for series in range(len(y)):\n",
    "        ax.plot(x, y[series][0],  y[series][1], label=y[series][2], linewidth=2)\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Add titles, labels and fix the x axis values to display correctly\n",
    "    ax.set_title(title)\n",
    "    ax.set_xlabel(x.name)\n",
    "    ax.set_ylabel(y[0][0].name)\n",
    "    ax.set_xticks(ax.get_xticks()[::90])\n",
    "    plt.xticks(rotation=45)\n",
    "    plt.legend()\n",
    "    \n",
    "    plt.show() "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a2010de1-544f-4b1f-9340-b93e943c9361",
   "metadata": {
    "jp-MarkdownHeadingCollapsed": true
   },
   "source": [
    "#### Temperature over time & Moving average"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 214,
   "id": "292201c3-cab8-4352-b779-3b45f42b623b",

    "#### Comparison of moving Averages"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "9837387b-21c7-441f-8e4e-d6858a4cf606",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Before doing a correlation analysis, I thought it might be a good idea to see if we can visualize any correlation in the data. Are there any matching trends,<br> \n",
    "or are the two series perhaps inverse to one another or always in-sync. Below we compare both of the series moving averages that we calculated above to see <br> \n",
    "if we can spot any similarities."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 221,
   "id": "95325376-6804-44f9-bb10-dad20026a51e",

    "# Create a second axis for the plot\n",
    "ax2 = ax.twinx()\n",
    "\n",
    "# Plot the first series to the first axis and the second series to the second axis\n",
    "ax.plot(climate_data.Date, temp_moving_avg, \"r\")\n",
    "ax2.plot(climate_data.Date, prec_moving_avg, \"b\")\n",
    "\n",

    "ax.set_xlabel(\"Date\")\n",

    "ax2.set_ylabel(\"Precipitation\", color= \"b\", fontsize=24)\n",
    "ax.set_xticks(ax.get_xticks()[::90])\n",
    "ax.tick_params(axis='x', rotation=45)\n",
    "plt.grid()\n",
    "plt.show() \n"
   ]

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "c68349d1-bafd-472a-8cf3-e8c6b14aac77",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In general it would seem that there is very little correlation between the two series. Towards the middle of the chart we can see <br>\n",
    "a small amount of inverse correlation with the temperature dropping to its lowest average and the precipitation rising to one of its peaks. <br>\n",
    "But this seems to be the only itme the two series act in such an obvious inverse manner like this. Towards the end of the chart we do see that <br>\n",
    "both data series start to rend downwards in what appears to be somewhat of a lock step manner, but when compared to the rest of the dataset, this <br>\n",
    "one moment in time is not enough to make any meaningful predictictions or assumptions on whether or not there is a connection from one dataset to <br>\n",
    "the other. Lets now use pandas .corr function to see if there is any correlation between the original sets of climate data."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a264facd-6365-42ab-b528-1c258f28ae15",
   "metadata": {
    "jp-MarkdownHeadingCollapsed": true
   },
   "source": [
    "### Task 4. Correlation analysis"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "0b97f906-5693-41e3-bc19-ba92859517c9",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "To calculate the correlation between the temperature and precipitation we need to:\n",
    "1. Get the averages of our two series\n",
    "2. Calculate the difference between each of the values of our series and their average's\n",
    "3. Multiply those two differences together.\n",
    "4. Add the sum of every product from step 3 together\n",
    "5. Divide the number produced in step 4 by the size of the whole series to get the covariance\n",
    "6. Now divide the covariance by the product of both standard deviations of our two series\n",
    "7. You now have the correlation coefficient, (time to drop out and go to wall street!)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 226,
   "id": "40e9f160-f044-4fcf-8b8b-ff0a9514f902",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Calculated Correlation between Temperature and Precipitation\n",
      "0.01644832\n",
      "\n",
      "Pandas Built in Correlation between Temperature and Precipitation\n",
      "0.01644799\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Now lets go through the above steps and calculate the correlation between the temperature and precipitation\n",
    "\n",
    "# Get the mean for the series\n",
    "temp_mean = calc_mean(temperature)\n",
    "prec_mean = calc_mean(precipitation)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Create a list of all the differences of one series multiplied by the differences of the other series\n",
    "covar_ls = [((temperature[i]-temp_mean) * (precipitation[i]-prec_mean)) for i in range(len(temperature))]\n",
    "\n",
    "# Iterate and add together all of the above calculated products\n",
    "sum = 0\n",
    "for entry in covar_ls:\n",
    "    sum += entry\n",
    "\n",
    "# Divide the sumation by the total number of entries to create the covariance\n",
    "covariance = sum/(len(covar_ls))\n",
    "\n",
    "# Divide the covariance by the product of the standard deviations of our pandas series\n",
    "correlation = covariance / (calc_std(temperature) * calc_std(precipitation))\n",
    "\n",
    "# Print out the results\n",
    "print(\"Calculated Correlation between Temperature and Precipitation\")\n",
    "print(round(correlation, 8))\n",
    "\n",
    "# Print a blank line\n",
    "print()\n",
    "\n",
    "# Alternatively we could just use the .corr function built into pandas to achieve the same result.\n",
    "print(\"Pandas Built in Correlation between Temperature and Precipitation\")\n",
    "pand_corr = temperature.corr(precipitation)\n",
    "print(round(pand_corr, 8))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "2d8bb655-378b-46f4-81e9-9844585475d7",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "This correlation metric shows us that there is practically no correlation at all between our data series as <br>\n",
    "a score of 1 would be considered a perfect correlation and -1 would be a negative correlation, and 0 indicates <br>\n",
    "no correlation at all. Our data set is very close to zero, indicating practically no correlation exists."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 229,
   "id": "4e02f237-fc3e-4358-bb76-51c4d324bff7",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1000x800 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Create a figure\n",
    "fig, ax=plt.subplots(figsize=(10,8))\n",
    "\n",
    "# Add a scatter plot to our figure\n",
    "ax.scatter(temperature, precipitation, color=\"c\" ,edgecolor=\"b\" ,s=80)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Create our linear regression using the formula for a linear function\n",
    "# y = m*x+b and add it to our plot\n",
    "m, b = np.polyfit(temperature, precipitation, 1)\n",
    "ax.plot(temperature, m*temperature+b, \"m\")\n",
    "\n",
    "# Add titles and labels\n",
    "ax.set_title(\"Relationship between Temperature and Precipitation\", fontsize=20)\n",
    "ax.set_xlabel(\"Temperature\")\n",
    "ax.set_ylabel(\"Percipitation\", rotation=90)\n",
    "ax.annotate(\"Regression Line\", xy=(25.5,3.2), xytext=(29,5), arrowprops=dict(facecolor=\"black\", shrink=0.05))\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a4f9812a-a78b-44f9-82bc-a28685367a0f",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Finally looking at our scatter plot of all of our data points combined, we see what has already been<br>\n",

    "line sitting right where our regression line is sitting."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "94ee7a0a-aa38-44e1-802d-838bc48caaa4",

   "source": [
    "### Task5. Extreme Events Analysis"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 233,
   "id": "9635f0d4-4232-4c92-b187-2ee748245aa3",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Create a function to plot our results\n",
    "def extreme_events(series):\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    Takes a pandas series, sorts it in both ascending and decending order\n",
    "    then plots the top ten results from each sorting to a subplot of two\n",
    "    scatter plots. \n",
    "    param: series, Series - A pandas data series\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    # Use pandas sort_values function to sort the values\n",
    "    highest = series.sort_values(ascending=False)\n",
    "    lowest = series.sort_values()\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Create the figure\n",
    "    fig, ax=plt.subplots(1,2,figsize=(14,5))\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Create a numpy array for the 10 \n",
    "    time = np.arange(0,10) \n",
    "\n",
    "    ax[0].scatter(time, highest[:10], color=\"m\")\n",
    "    ax[1].scatter(time, lowest[:10], color=\"c\")\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Add titles and labels to all of our plots\n",
    "    ax[0].set_title(f\"Highest {series.name}\", fontsize=15)\n",
    "    ax[1].set_title(f\"Lowest {series.name}\", fontsize=15)\n",
    "\n",
    "    ax[0].set_xlabel(\"Days\", fontsize=12)\n",
    "    ax[1].set_xlabel(\"Days\", fontsize=12)\n",
    "    ax[0].set_ylabel(series.name, fontsize=12)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 235,
   "id": "0f1d8612-837d-43fc-860f-fd20086ea8ae",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [

     "data": {
      "image/png": "",

      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"

   "source": [
    "# Call the plotting function for temperature\n",
    "extreme_events(temperature)"

    "### Final Analysis"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "420f45a1-4ff8-4158-8800-43ce3a10868c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Overall this was an interesting experiment we performed on two years of temperature and precipitation data. We learnt that <br>\n",
    "there does not seem to be much correlation between the day to day temperatures and rainfall (according to the dataset we used) <br>\n",
    "Perhaps with a bigger dataset with different weather variables that is collected over a much longer timeframe (100s of years), we  <br>\n",
    "may perhaps be able to see a much stronger correlation between variables or a more cyclic pattern of the weather over time, or perhaps <br>\n",
    "not, our experiements in this notebook suggest otherwise for now."
